Relaxed Online SVMs for Spam Filtering 
content:
1 ABSTRACT :
1-1:Spam is a key problem in electronic communication, including large scale email systems and the growing number of blogs .
1-2:Content based filtering is one reliable method of combating this threat in its various forms, but some academic researchers and industrial practitioners disagree on how best to filter spam .
1-3:The former have advocated the use of Support Vector Machines (SVMs) for content based filtering, as this machine learning methodology gives state of the art performance for text classification .
1-4:However, similar performance gains have yet to be demonstrated for online spam filtering .
1-5:Additionally, practitioners cite the high cost of SVMs as reason to prefer faster (if less statistically robust) Bayesian methods .
1-6:In this paper, we offer a resolution to this controversy .
1-7:First, we show that online SVMs indeed give state of the art classification performance on online spam filtering on large benchmark data sets .
1-8:Second, we show that nearly equivalent performance may be achieved by a Relaxed Online SVM at greatly reduced computational cost .
1-9:Our results are experimentally verified on email spam, blog spam, and splog detection tasks .
1-10:H.3.3 [Information Storage and Retrieval]: Information .
2 INTRODUCTION :
2-1:Electronic communication is increasingly plagued by unwanted or harmful content known as spam .
2-2:The most well known form of spam is email spam, which remains a major problem for large email systems .
2-3:Other forms of spam are also becoming problematic, including blog spam, in which spammers post unwanted comments in blogs [21], and splogs, which are fake blogs constructed to enable link spam with the hope of boosting the measured importance of a given webpage in the eyes of automated search engines [17] .
2-4:There are a variety of methods for identifying these many forms of spam, including compiling blacklists of known spammers, and conducting link analysis .
2-5:The approach of content analysis has shown particular promise and generality for combating spam .
2-6:In content analysis, the actual message text (often including hyper text and meta text, such as HTML and headers) is analyzed using machine learning techniques for text classification to determine if the given content is spam .
2-7:Content analysis has been widely applied in detecting email spam [11], and has also been used for identifying blog spam [21] and splogs [17] .
2-8:In this paper, we do not explore the related problem of link spam, which is currently best combated by link analysis [13] .
2-9:1.1 An Anti Spam Controversy The anti spam community has been divided on the choice of the best machine learning method for content based spam detection .
2-10:Academic researchers have tended to favor the use of Support Vector Machines (SVMs), a statistically robust machine learning method [7] which yields state of theart performance on general text classification [14] .
2-11:However, SVMs typically require training time that is quadratic in the number of training examples, and are impractical for largescale email systems .
2-12:Practitioners requiring content based spam filtering have typically chosen to use the faster (if less statistically robust) machine learning method of Naive Bayes text classification [11, 12, 20] .
2-13:This Bayesian method requires only linear training time, and is easily implemented in an online setting with incremental updates .
2-14:This allows a deployed system to easily adapt to a changing environment over time .
2-15:Other fast methods for spam filtering include compression models [1] and logistic regression [10] .
2-16:It has not yet been empirically demonstrated that SVMs give improved performance over these methods in an online spam detection setting [4] .
2-17:1.2 Contributions In this paper, we address the anti spam controversy and offer a potential resolution .
2-18:We first demonstrate that online SVMs do indeed provide state of the art spam detection through empirical tests on several large benchmark data sets of email spam .
2-19:We then analyze the effect of the tradeoff parameter in the SVM objective function, which shows that the expensive SVM methodology may, in fact, be overkill for spam detection .
2-20:We reduce the computational cost of SVM learning by relaxing this requirement on the maximum margin in online settings, and create a Relaxed Online SVM, ROSVM, appropriate for high performance content based spam filtering in large scale settings. .
3 SPAM AND ONLINE SVMS :
3-1:The controversy between academics and practitioners in spam filtering centers on the use of SVMs .
3-2:The former advocate their use, but have yet to demonstrate strong performance with SVMs on online spam filtering .
3-3:Indeed, the results of [4] show that, when used with default parameters, SVMs actually perform worse than other methods .
3-4:In this section, we review the basic workings of SVMs and describe a simple Online SVM algorithm .
3-5:We then show that Online SVMs indeed achieve state of the art performance on filtering email spam, blog comment spam, and splogs, so long as the tradeoff parameter C is set to a high value .
3-6:However, the cost of Online SVMs turns out to be prohibitive for largescale applications .
3-7:These findings motivate our proposal of Relaxed Online SVMs in the following section .
3-8:2.1 Background: SVMs SVMs are a robust machine learning methodology which has been shown to yield state of the art performance on text classification [14] .
3-9:by finding a hyperplane that separates two classes of data in data space while maximizing the margin between them .
3-10:We use the following notation to describe SVMs, which draws from [23] .
