3-26:Training SVMs, however, typically takes O(n2 ) time, for n training examples .
3-27:A variant for linear SVMs was recently proposed which trains in O(ns) time [15], but because this method has a high constant, we do not explore it here .
3-28:2.2 Online SVMs In many traditional machine learning applications, SVMs are applied in batch mode .
3-29:That is, an SVM is trained on an entire set of training data, and is then tested on a separate set of testing data .
3-30:Spam filtering is typically tested and deployed in an online setting, which proceeds incrementally .
3-31:Here, the learner classifies a new example, is told if its prediction is correct, updates its hypothesis accordingly, and then awaits a new example .
3-32:Online learning allows a deployed system to adapt itself in a changing environment .
3-33:Re training an SVM from scratch on the entire set of previously seen data for each new example is cost prohibitive .
3-34:However, using an old hypothesis as the starting point for re training reduces this cost considerably .
3-35:One method of incremental and decremental SVM learning was proposed in [2] .
3-36:Because we are only concerned with incremental learning, we apply a simpler algorithm for converting a batch SVM learner into an online SVM (see Figure 1 for pseudocode), which is similar to the approach of [16] .
3-37:Each time the Online SVM encounters an example that was poorly classified, it retrains using the old hypothesis as a starting point .
3-38:Note that due to the Karush Kuhn Tucker conditions, it is not necessary to re train on wellclassified examples that are outside the margins [23] .
3-39:We used Platt"s SMO algorithm [22] as a core SVM solver, because it is an iterative method that is well suited to converge quickly from a good initial hypothesis .
3-40:Because previous work (and our own initial testing) indicates that binary feature values give the best results for spam filtering [20, 9], we optimized our implementation of the Online SMO to exploit fast inner products with binary vectors .
3-41:1 2.3 Feature Mapping Spam Content Extracting machine learning features from text may be done in a variety of ways, especially when that text may include hyper content and meta content such as HTML and header information .
3-42:However, previous research has shown that simple methods from text classification, such as bag of words vectors, and overlapping character level n grams, can achieve strong results [9] .
