4-41:3.2 Reducing Number of Updates As noted before, the KKT conditions show that a well classified example will not change the hypothesis; thus it is not necessary to re train when we encounter such an example .
4-42:Under the KKT conditions, an example xi is considered well classified when yif(xi) > 1 .
4-43:If we re train on every example that is not well classified, our hyperplane will be guaranteed to be optimal at every step .
4-44:The number of re training updates can be reduced by relaxing the definition of well classified .
4-45:An example xi is now considered well classified when yif(xi) > M, for some 0 ≤ M ≤ 1 .
4-46:Here, each update still produces an optimal hyperplane .
4-47:The learner may encounter an example that lies within the margins, but farther from the margins than M .
4-48:Such an example means the hypothesis is no longer globally optimal for the data set, but it is considered good enough for continued use without immediate retraining .
4-49:This update procedure is similar to that used by variants of the Perceptron algorithm [18] .
4-50:In the extreme case, we can set M = 0, which creates a mistake driven Online SVM .
4-51:In the experimental section, we show that this version of Online SVMs, which updates only on actual errors, does not significantly degrade performance on content based spam detection, but does significantly reduce cost .
4-52:3.3 Reducing Iterations As an iterative solver, SMO makes repeated passes over the data set to optimize the objective function .
4-53:SMO has one main loop, which can alternate between passing over the entire data set, or the smaller active set of current support vectors [22] .
4-54:Successive iterations of this loop bring the hyperplane closer to an optimal value .
4-55:However, it is possible that these iterations provide less benefit than their expense justifies .
4-56:That is, a close first approximation may be good enough .
4-57:We introduce a parameter T to control the maximum number of iterations we allow .
4-58:As we will see in the experimental section, this parameter can be set as low as 1 with little impact on the quality of results, providing computational savings. .
5 EXPERIMENTS :
5-1:In Section 2, we argued that the strong performance on content based spam detection with SVMs with a high value of C show that the maximum margin criteria is overkill, incurring unnecessary computational cost .
5-2:In Section 3, we proposed ROSVM to address this issue, as both of these methods trade away guarantees on the maximum margin hyperplane in return for reduced computational cost .
5-3:In this section, we test these methods on the same benchmark data sets to see if state of the art performance may be achieved by these less costly methods .
5-4:We find that ROSVM is capable of achieving these high levels of performance with greatly reduced cost .
5-5:Our main tests on content based spam detection are performed on large benchmark sets of email data .
5-6:We then apply these methods on the smaller data sets of blog comment spam and blogs, with similar performance .
