5-13:4.1.1 Testing Reduced Size For our first ROSVM test, we experiment on the effect of reducing the size of the optimization problem by only considering the p most recent examples, as described in the previous section .
5-14:For this test, we use the same 4 gram mappings as for the reference experiments in Section 2, with the same value C = 100 .
5-15:We test a range of values p in a coarse grid search .
5-16:Figure 5 reports the effect of the buffer size p in relationship to the (1 ROCA)% performance measure (top), and the number of CPU seconds required (bottom) .
5-17:The results show that values of p < 100 do result in degraded performance, although they evaluate very quickly .
5-18:However, p values from 500 to 10,000 perform almost as well as the original Online SMO (represented here as p = 100, 000), at dramatically reduced computational cost .
5-19:These results are important for making state of the art performance on large scale content based spam detection practical with online SVMs .
5-20:Ordinarily, the training time would grow quadratically with the number of seen examples .
5-21:However, fixing a value of p ensures that the training time is independent of the size of the data set .
5-22:Furthermore, a lookback buffer allows the filter to adjust to concept drift .
