5-27:4.1.2 Testing Reduced Iterations In the second ROSVM test, we experiment with reducing the number of iterations .
5-28:Our initial tests showed that the maximum number of iterations used by Online SMO was rarely much larger than 10 on content based spam detection; thus we tested values of T = {1, 2, 5, ∞} .
5-29:Other parameters were identical to the original Online SVM tests .
5-30:The results on this test were surprisingly stable (see Figure 6) .
5-31:Reducing the maximum number of SMO iterations per update had essentially no impact on classification performance, but did result in a moderate increase in speed .
5-32:This suggests that any additional iterations are spent attempting to find improvements to a hyperplane that is already very close to optimal .
5-33:These results show that for content based spam detection, we can reduce computational cost by allowing only a single SMO iteration (that is, T = 1) with effectively equivalent performance .
5-34:4.1.3 Testing Reduced Updates For our third ROSVM experiment, we evaluate the impact of adjusting the parameter M to reduce the total number of updates .
5-35:As noted before, when M = 1, the hyperplane is globally optimal at every step .
5-36:Reducing M allows a slightly inconsistent hyperplane to persist until it encounters an example for which it is too inconsistent .
5-37:We tested values of M from 0 to 1, at increments of 0.1 .
5-38:(Note that we used p = 10000 to decrease the cost of evaluating these tests.) The results for these tests are appear in Figure 7, and show that there is a slight degradation in performance with reduced values of M, and that this degradation in performance is accompanied by an increase in efficiency .
