5-42:4.2 Online SVMs and ROSVM We now compare ROSVM against Online SVMs on the email spam, blog comment spam, and splog detection tasks .
5-43:These experiments show comparable performance on these tasks, at radically different costs .
5-44:In the previous section, the effect of the different relaxation methods was tested separately .
5-45:Here, we tested these methods together to create a full implementation of ROSVM .
5-46:We chose the values p = 10000, T = 1, M = 0.8 for the email spam detection tasks .
5-47:Note that these parameter values were selected as those allowing ROSVM to achieve comparable performance results with Online SVMs, in order to test total difference in computational cost .
5-48:The splog and blog data sets were much smaller, so we set p = 100 for these tasks to allow meaningful comparisons between the reduced size and full size optimization problems .
5-49:Because these values were not hand tuned, both generalization performance and runtime results are meaningful in these experiments .
5-50:4.2.1 Experimental Setup We compared Online SVMs and ROSVM on email spam, blog comment spam, and splog detection .
5-51:For the email spam, we used the two large benchmark corpora, trec05p 1 and trec06p, in the standard online ordering .
5-52:We randomly ordered both the blog comment spam corpus and the splog corpus to create online learning tasks .
