6-8:The high values of C required for best performance with SVMs show that the margin maximization of Online SVMs is overkill for this task
6-9:Thus, we have proposed a less expensive alternative, ROSVM, that relaxes this maximum margin requirement, and produces nearly equivalent results
6-10:These methods are efficient enough for large scale filtering of contentbased spam in its many forms
6-11:It is natural to ask why the task of content based spam detection gets strong performance from ROSVM
6-12:After all, not all data allows the relaxation of SVM requirements
6-13:We conjecture that email spam, blog comment spam, and splogs all share the characteristic that a subset of features are particularly indicative of content being either spam or not spam
6-14:These indicative features may be sparsely represented in the data set, because of spam methods such as word obfuscation, in which common spam words are intentionally misspelled in an attempt to reduce the effectiveness of word based spam detection
6-15:Maximizing the margin may cause these sparsely represented features to be ignored, creating an overall reduction in performance
6-16:It appears that spam data is highly separable, allowing ROSVM to be successful with high values of C and little effort given to maximizing the margin
6-17:Future work will determine how applicable relaxed SVMs are to the general problem of text classification
6-18:Finally, we note that the success of relaxed SVM methods for content based spam detection is a result that depends on the nature of spam data, which is potentially subject to change
6-19:Although it is currently true that ham and spam are linearly separable given an appropriate feature space, this assumption may be subject to attack
6-20:While our current methods appear robust against primitive attacks along these lines, such as the good word attack [24], we must explore the feasibility of more sophisticated attacks.
